<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-420-663  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 420 663.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC orders phone rate cuts, reduces access fee.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionPriceGovernment RegulationGovernment AgencyTelecommunicationsLegal IssuesPrice Cutting.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FCC ORDERS PHONE RATE CUTS, REDUCES ACCESS FEE WASHINGTON, D.C., U.S.A., 1990JUN 20 (NB) -- By cutting the fees charged to long distance companies foraccess to local phone numbers, the Federal Communications Commission isgiving consumers a $1.1 billion break on their phone bills for the yearstarting July 1.andP;  The FCC estimates those charges came to $19 billion lastyear.andM;The reductions are nearly $700 million more than the local phone companiesthemselves proposed in April.andP;  The FCC's common carrier bureau found thatinaccurate projections of demand and costs resulted in excessive rates ofreturn for local phone companies.andP;  In particular, the FCC staff found, thelocal phone companies overestimated their depreciation expenses.andM;The FCC also found that several of the Bells had misallocated their lobbyingcosts to operating expense accounts, a charge which Allnet has formally madebefore the FCC concerning Southwestern Bell.andP;  This time, however, the FCCfound that BellSouth, Ameritech, NYNEX and Pacific Telesis also charged ratepayers for some of their lobbying costs.andP;  MCI had asked the FCC to study thegeneral question of whether the Bells were lobbying Congress at the expenseof their customers.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900629/Press Contact: FCC Press Office, 202- 632-5050)</TEXT></DOC>